13th July

Examining the valve equaiton, one can see it takes the following three forms depending on whether density is evaluated at the upstream condition, average of the upstream or downstream condtions, or the down stream condition. For a given mass flow (y) we get multiplicity in (x -- pressure ratio pd/pu) for the last two modes. Perhaps this explains the convergence troubles. Started using the upstream conditions for density of fluid and my convergence issues are no longer present for Adsorber and parallel valve problem.

file: Media/IdealGases/Common/package.mo

function extends setSmoothState
  "Return thermodynamic state so that it smoothly 
    approximates: if x > 0 then state_a else state_b"
  algorithm
      state := ThermodynamicState(
        p = Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.p, state_b.p, x_small), 
        T = Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.T, state_b.T, x_small), 
        X = Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.X, state_b.X, x_small));
        annotation(Inline = true, smoothOrder = 2);
end setSmoothState;

Ravi's mod follows so that smoothStep on X 
   which is not a scalar is properly handled
*/
 state := ThermodynamicState(
        p=Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.p, state_b.p, x_small),
        T=Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.T, state_b.T, x_small),
        X={Media.Common.smoothStep(x, state_a.X[i], state_b.X[i], x_small)
                                       for i in 1:size(state_a.X,1)});


Listing of Media.Common.smoothStep function

function smoothStep "Approximation of a general step, 
such that the characteristic is continuous and differentiable"
  extends Modelica.Icons.Function;
  input Real x "Abscissa value";
  input Real y1 "Ordinate value for x > 0";
  input Real y2 "Ordinate value for x < 0";
  input Real x_small(min = 0) = 1e-5 "Approximation of step 
            for -x_small <= x <= x_small; x_small > 0 required";
  output Real y "Ordinate value to approximate 
                  y = if x > 0 then y1 else y2";
algorithm
  y := smooth(1, if x > x_small then y1 else 
                      if x < (-x_small) then y2 else
                      if abs(x_small) > 0 then 
                        x / x_small * ((x / x_small) ^ 2 - 3) 
                        * (y2 - y1) 
                        / 4 + (y1 + y2) / 2 else (y1 + y2) / 2);
  annotation(Inline = true, smoothOrder = 1

I could show that the change works as well as the original. It implies that the smoothStep function can handle vectors despite the fact the code does not indicate so.

29th Oct.

Some solver convergence issues on the above problem are due to valve moving to the limits of the valve position. Any numerical noise near the lower bound produces negative valve position causing solver to reset the inital guess. Also, having 0% H2O in gas mixture also has the same effect. Lesson ... don't let variables go near the limits. (especially if you don't want negative values for composition, .... clumsy explanation ... tidy this up . But now I know how the solver works. (let the valve leak a bit, and let it open to no more than 99.99) Phew two months passed . What did I do??? Ah... worked on operator training GUI.

Exploratory code
model plant
/*
  Author: Ravi Saripalli
Get Temperature of gas mixture given enthalpy, pressure and composition

*/
    
    
  package Medium = Modelica.Media.IdealGases.MixtureGases.CombustionAir;
  import Modelica.Media.IdealGases.Common.MixtureGasNasa.h_TX;

  Medium.ThermodynamicState state ;
  Medium.SpecificEnthalpy h ;
    
  constant Integer option = 3  ;

equation

    h = 600000;

if option == 1 then     // works 
// invariably calls T_hX function which in turn 
//uses internal singleNonlinear eqn. solver
//  backend Translation of which fails on some  instances
    state = Medium.setState_phX(1e5, h, {0.79, 0.21});
elseif option == 2 then  // works ... and avoids T_hX calls
    state.p = 1e5 ;
    state.X = {0.79, 0.21} ;
    h - Medium.specificEnthalpy(state) = 0;
else // fails at index reduction ... why?
     state.p = 1e5 ;
     state.X = {0.79, 0.21} ;
     h - h_TX(state.T, state.X) = 0 ;
 end if;                                     
end plant;

  • Initialize Composition, State, pressure, Temp etc at Media level in the main model. Looks like it trickles down to the individual model instances ... it appears Any start value attributes at base model have lower precedence (makes sense)
  • Min, Max values are monitored and the solver will try to honour them if possible but if a solution exists outside the bounds it will accept it with just warning ... hidden in log. Using Assert call with "warning" or "error" level should be considered. But error terminates the task that exerts the alert. ... explore more
  • There is a neat way to impose inequality constraings as equalities (using min max functions) then adding the square of the residuals of these converted equations to the original equation will ensure no root that violates the constraints exists. \lmada * (Resid_orginal eqn.)^2 + \gamma * (Resid_constraints)^2=0

13th Jan. 2016

  • Explorations over Christmas break on Adsorber model revealed that Darcy eqn. implementation was erroneous. The way Kappa was defined it should have appeared in denominator Instead it was left in the numerator. Once this error was rectified pressure drop in the bed ceased to be significant.
  • Further reading on Adsorber modelling revealed that the problem is set up as micro-pore diffusion controlled process. That is at the crystalline level. The pore diffusion and mass transfer film diffusion resistences were assumed negligible. Apparently that is valid for Zeolite X5. The kinetic parametes given in the book correspond to the degree of micro-pore diffusivity. It appears that the kinetic parameter need to be adjusted with pressure (reduces with pressure since diffusivity reduces with pressure).
  • After fixing the bug, further exploration revealed that setting initial guess values of Collocation coefficients makes the integration too slow or impossible. I think the non-linear eqn. set changes for initialization or restart at discontinuities depending what variables are given initial guess.(not initial conidtions).
  • Updated OpenModelica to work in parallel mode. (Simple just add CFLAGS="-g -O2 -fopenmp") and then run configure. Also, using make -j8 (if you have 8 cores) helps speed up compiliation too. Updated modelica source to the latest. T_hX still requires to be applied to Modelica Library 3.2.1.
  • Tried to see if I can switch to Dymola. But that proved difficult as its compiler does not support many of the features I used in OpenModelica. (still Modelica Compliant... dymola is lagging behind)
  • Implemented discrete clock granularity to my sequencing of valves as it is clear that the cycle times for the OBOGS is of the order of seconds not minutes. For some reason the best O2 concentration I could get at sea level at operating pressures of 3bar is about 38%O2 with single bed. Is this because I dont purge with product gas ??
    • It is now critical that I have some idea of the actual purge and pressurization times along with valve characteristics of the device.

within ThermoS.Uops.PSA;
//Author: Ravi Saripalli

record bedParamsRec

  constant Integer  Nc = 2      ; // Number species in Gas media 
  constant Real R = 8314.5      ; // Universal Gas Constant Pa. m3/(C kgmol)

  Real Pref = 1e5               ; // Reference pressure (Pa)
  Real Tref = 300               ; // Reference Temperature (K) 
  Real Uref = 1.0               ; // Refernece Gas Velocity (m/s)
  
  Real Diff = 1e-3              ; // Axial dispersion Coeff  (m2/sec) 
  Real mu   = 2.0e-5            ; // Air viscosity (kg/m.s)
  Real dp   = 1.0e-3            ; // Adsorbent particle size (m)
  Real Tbed = 300               ; // Adsorber temperature (K)

  Real voidage = 0.5            ; // Bed voidage
  Real L    = 0.25              ; // Adsorber Bed length (m)
  Real dia  = 0.2               ; // Adsorber Bed diameter(m)
  
  Real qs[Nc]  = {5.26, 5.26}        ; // Langmuir Saturation Concentration (kgmol/m3)
  Real hk[Nc]  = {14.8, 4.7}         ; // Henry's Constants (dim. less) (= qs * b)
  Real k_m[Nc] = {19.7, 62.0}        ; // External Mass transfer rate s (1/s)
  
  // Derived quantities
  Real csArea = 3.147*dia*dia/4 ; // Bed CrossSectional Area (m2)   

  Real Cref    = Pref / (R * Tref)             ; // Reference Molar Concentration (kgmol/m3)
  Real b[Nc]   = hk ./ qs                      ; // Units m3/kgmol
  Real Kozney  = 180 * mu * (1 - voidage)^2    
                          / ( dp * dp * voidage^3 )    ; // KozneyCarman Eqn. Coeff. (pressure grad/vel)
  >
  // These are the basic params the core model needs
  Real Epsilon = (1 - voidage) / voidage     ;
  Real Km[Nc]  = k_m * (L / Uref)            ;// Dim.less Mass trasnfer rate 
  Real Kappa   = Kozney * L * Uref / Pref    ;// dp*/dz* = - Kappa* v*   (dimensionless)
  Real Pe      = L * Uref / Diff             ;// Peclet number
  Real B[Nc]   = b * Cref                    ;// Normalized b
  Real Qs[Nc]  = qs / Cref                   ;// Normalized Saturation Concentration 
  Real Tb      = Tbed / Tref                 ;// Adsorber temperature (isothermal)

end bedParamsRec;
  • Running a single bed with short cycle (of the order of 5 to 10 sec) does improve the product quality as opposed to much larger time cycles I was using before. (40sec). Keeping the cycle time to 5 sec with (1,1,3) breakup for purge, pressurize and feed phases I am able to find peak O2 concentrations of the order of 40% at pressure level of 3bar.
  • Implemented descrete clock granularity to enable resolution short cycles times. The effect of the clock granularity was not very significant on the results. But simulations take much longer
  • Lowering the purge pressure from 1bar to 0.5bar did not alter results. Further reading seems to suggest that unless we purge with the enriched gas we may not be able to improve the product quality furhter. This can only be verified conveniently when I move to duel bed runs with equalizaiton line between beds during purge phase.
  • Chaning the inital bed adsorbed concentrations made a huge difference to the product quality with O2 peak product concentrations changing from 40 - 70 - 80 % progressively for saturated, unsaturated and virgin beds. Normalized saturated bed adsorbate concentrations are Q=[N2=11.2,O2=0.7]. These were based on numerical experiments with both feed and product reservoirs at 1 bar. The following trend shows the effect of inital bed conditions. This is only significant if our cycle is such that we are not able to balance rated of accumulation of n2 in the bed with the corresponding purge during a cycle.

14th Nov. 2016

Simulaiton worked well even with N=12. Over the weekend, thought of the possible pitfalls in my adsorber model. Although my adsorber boundary conditions for compositon are robust, (the boundary condition that conserves molar flow across the boundary under in/out/and noflow conditions). As for the pressure boundary condition of set pressures (p[N]=Pout, p=[N-1]=Pin) hold good only when abs(flowRate)>0. For no flow conditon one need to impose zero pressure gradient. (dirichlet to Neuman conditions). This may be the cause of hiccups at certain times when the solvers hits exact no flow conditons. It is observed solver gets stuck when pressure in the bed gets very close to the reservoir pressure (when the flow is negligible)

With the following code in adsorber b.c's ran twin bed model, with the valve position limits between 99-1% at N=12. Problem took 140min for 100sec simulation. 

 

// Pressure Boundary Conditions
         0 = if (inlet.m_flow == 0.0) then Coef_p[:] * vTz[:, N-1]
             else Coef_p[:] * vT[:, N-1] - p_in ;    // Inlet  pressure 
          

          0 = if (outlet.m_flow == 0.0) then Coef_p[:] * vTz[:, N]
              else Coef_p[:] * vT[:, N] - p_out ;    // outlet  pressure
It had glitches in outflow (large spikes) that are unrealistic. Corresponding valve positions were negative. The solver did struggle at these points with NLS solver not converging but integration proceeded to 100sec. Is there a bug in the solver? Now it is clear that my B.C change in the code did not make any difference. In fact, when the flow is zero pressure can still be specified as long as the valve is open to some degree because the pressure difference under those conditons across the valve is zero. It is only when it is completely closed valve equation ceases to apply. Flow through valve is zero, and enthalpies, pressures etc. across the valve no longer are related.

16th Nov. 2016

Changed valve equation to eliminate conditional statements to cover choking region with max function. and then rerun case with minimum valve opening back to 1%. Case1 problem solved in 60minutes and the solution was smooth with no glitches. Sover had not issues what so ever. 

 

    prat = min(inlet.p, outlet.p) / max(inlet.p, outlet.p) ;

// Make Valve equaiton continuous and differentiable both near zero flows
// and choked conditions

    if (Compressible) then
       inlet.m_flow = cv * charF  *  sqrt(abs(med.d) * max(inlet.p, outlet.p)) * sign(inlet.p - outlet.p) 
                         * regRoot(1 - max(prat, 0.5), dpTol) ;       // Covers Choking Region (with C0 continuity)
    else
       inlet.m_flow = cv * charF  *  sqrt(abs(med.d * inlet.p)) * regRoot(1 - outlet.p/inlet.p, dpTol) ;
    end if;
